<task id="AIPU2-016" project="Spaarke AI Platform Unification R2">
  <metadata>
    <title>Build Capability Validation (Permissions, Kill Switch, Context)</title>
    <phase>2A</phase>
    <tags>bff-api, ai, security</tags>
    <status>not-started</status>
    <estimated-effort>3 hours</estimated-effort>
    <dependencies>AIPU2-010</dependencies>
    <parallel-safe>false</parallel-safe>
  </metadata>
  <prompt>
    Build BFF-side capability validation that enforces three safety gates before a capability is activated:
    (1) user permission check — does the caller's Entra ID token contain the required role or group membership
    for this capability; (2) tenant toggle — is the capability enabled for this specific Dataverse environment;
    (3) kill switch — is the capability globally disabled via a feature flag. Blocked activations are silently
    excluded from the active capability set (the user receives a reduced capability set, not an error) but are
    logged for audit. A fourth check — context compatibility — validates that the conversation's current
    context (e.g. matter loaded, document present) satisfies the capability's preconditions.
  </prompt>
  <role>Senior .NET security-aware backend engineer familiar with Spaarke auth patterns and ADR-008.</role>
  <goal>
    Unauthorized or unavailable capabilities are silently excluded from the manifest view presented to the
    router and prompt builder. Blocked activations are logged with user ID, capability name, and reason.
    No error is surfaced to the user for a blocked capability.
  </goal>
  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>.claude/constraints/auth.md</file>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-008-endpoint-filters.md</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Capabilities/CapabilityManifest.cs</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Infrastructure/Graph/GraphClientFactory.cs</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>
  <steps>
    <step>Read auth.md and ADR-008 to understand the permission model: roles come from the caller's JWT claims, tenant isolation is enforced via environment URL matching, feature flags come from IConfiguration or a feature management service.</step>
    <step>Create ICapabilityValidator.cs interface with: Task&lt;IReadOnlyList&lt;CapabilityManifestEntry&gt;&gt; FilterAsync(IReadOnlyList&lt;CapabilityManifestEntry&gt; candidates, CapabilityValidationContext ctx, CancellationToken ct).</step>
    <step>Create CapabilityValidationContext.cs record: ClaimsPrincipal User, string TenantEnvironmentUrl, IReadOnlyDictionary&lt;string, object&gt; ConversationContext (e.g. MatterLoaded, DocumentPresent).</step>
    <step>Create CapabilityValidator.cs implementing ICapabilityValidator. Apply four checks in order for each candidate: (a) Kill switch — check IFeatureManager or IConfiguration["AiCapabilities:KillSwitch:{name}"] = "true"; (b) Tenant toggle — check CapabilityManifestEntry.TenantRestrictions (empty list = all tenants allowed); (c) User permission — check required roles against ClaimsPrincipal.IsInRole(); (d) Context compatibility — check required context keys from entry metadata against ConversationContext.</step>
    <step>For each excluded capability, log at Information level: "Capability '{name}' excluded for user '{userId}': {reason}". Use structured logging with properties CapabilityName, UserId, ExclusionReason.</step>
    <step>Emit OTEL counter ai_capability_validation_excluded_total with labels capability_name, reason (kill_switch | tenant_toggle | permission | context).</step>
    <step>Integrate CapabilityValidator into CapabilityRoutingMiddleware: before calling ICapabilityRouter.RouteAsync, call ICapabilityValidator.FilterAsync to produce the effective capability list for this request. Pass the filtered list to the router instead of the full manifest.</step>
    <step>Register ICapabilityValidator as scoped (per-request, since it uses ClaimsPrincipal) in AddAiCapabilitiesModule().</step>
    <step>Write unit tests: kill switch excludes capability, tenant mismatch excludes, missing role excludes, missing context key excludes, all checks pass → capability included.</step>
    <step>Run `dotnet build` and `dotnet test --filter "CapabilityValidat"` to verify.</step>
  </steps>
  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion>Capabilities with active kill switch are excluded for all users.</criterion>
    <criterion>Capabilities restricted to specific tenant URLs are excluded for users on other tenants.</criterion>
    <criterion>Capabilities requiring a role not held by the caller are excluded silently.</criterion>
    <criterion>Capabilities requiring context keys (e.g. MatterLoaded=true) are excluded when context is absent.</criterion>
    <criterion>Every exclusion is logged at Information level with CapabilityName, UserId, and ExclusionReason.</criterion>
    <criterion>OTEL counter ai_capability_validation_excluded_total incremented per exclusion.</criterion>
    <criterion>No HTTP error is returned to the caller when capabilities are excluded.</criterion>
    <criterion>Unit tests pass: `dotnet test --filter "CapabilityValidat"`.</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>
</task>
